Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

- HLO real/imag instructions with non-complex inputs can be simplified to copy/zero.
- Non complex inputs are not supported in MLIR LMHLO dialect, so simplifying these
  operations upfront helps avoid creating invalid MLIR, as well as can enable other
  optimizations.

so the attributes can be accessed easily.

Change-Id: Ibff688202c484abaab034e2a7f58ca6adfb4e3c7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hfahrudin/tensorflow/commits/5eace4eb1746ca9314d1a7326084ec5285678972"},{"sha":"a297cd670d58149763d3eba82b626a4e9d5c55da","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Disable MLIR bridge in the second phase for non entry functions

Currently, the MLIR bridge is enabled based on the graph analysis for each function individually so it may happen that a parent function is not compiled with MLIR but function attached to any op like WhileOp in the function is compiled with MLIR. This makes the logic complex and can expose new bugs if we disable MLIR bridge in the first phase.

The downside of this is that second phase of the bridge will be rolled out slowly and with coarser grained forks. This is what we want in the beginning to limit bridge rollout to the first phase and later this can be tweaked, if required.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362599513
Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

Change-Id: Ie44b53d3eff2a19ea76f643ffd977997ce69d217","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/5097e6b36350f16032db950792c54f50a5385ec9"},{"sha":"0b45981fc6525c0b677bb019566fcf12445142f2","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Generalize tf-rewrite-tpu-embedding-ops pass to handle embedding ops within regions

Currently, the pass assumes embedding ops to be directly in a function and was working only because functional control flow to regions pass introduces call functions so the embedding ops ended up being in a separate function.

The above won't be true for this pass's usage to rewrite these ops in MLIR module before converting it to Graph for compilation using the old bridge second phase.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362599513
Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

[{"sha":"0b45981fc6525c0b677bb019566fcf12445142f2","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Generalize tf-rewrite-tpu-embedding-ops pass to handle embedding ops within regions

Currently, the pass assumes embedding ops to be directly in a function and was working only because functional control flow to regions pass introduces call functions so the embedding ops ended up being in a separate function.

The above won't be true for this pass's usage to rewrite these ops in MLIR module before converting it to Graph for compilation using the old bridge second phase.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

[{"sha":"0b45981fc6525c0b677bb019566fcf12445142f2","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Generalize tf-rewrite-tpu-embedding-ops pass to handle embedding ops within regions

Currently, the pass assumes embedding ops to be directly in a function and was working only because functional control flow to regions pass introduces call functions so the embedding ops ended up being in a separate function.

The above won't be true for this pass's usage to rewrite these ops in MLIR module before converting it to Graph for compilation using the old bridge second phase.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

[{"sha":"e065755f0848e47322a21956a5e68a69562e77a8","author":{"name":"annarev","email":"ea79b6e1b24599611d5cbebff445e3f8620f2c85@google.com"},"message":"Add use_bfc_allocator parameter to StreamExecutor C API","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/e065755f0848e47322a21956a5e68a69562e77a8"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

Change-Id: Ie44b53d3eff2a19ea76f643ffd977997ce69d217","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/5097e6b36350f16032db950792c54f50a5385ec9"},{"sha":"0b45981fc6525c0b677bb019566fcf12445142f2","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Generalize tf-rewrite-tpu-embedding-ops pass to handle embedding ops within regions

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362599513
Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362599513
Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 359638762
Change-Id: Ibff688202c484abaab034e2a7f58ca6adfb4e3c7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/AdityaKane2001/tensorflow/commits/5eace4eb1746ca9314d1a7326084ec5285678972"},{"sha":"a297cd670d58149763d3eba82b626a4e9d5c55da","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Disable MLIR bridge in the second phase for non entry functions

Currently, the MLIR bridge is enabled based on the graph analysis for each function individually so it may happen that a parent function is not compiled with MLIR but function attached to any op like WhileOp in the function is compiled with MLIR. This makes the logic complex and can expose new bugs if we disable MLIR bridge in the first phase.

The downside of this is that second phase of the bridge will be rolled out slowly and with coarser grained forks. This is what we want in the beginning to limit bridge rollout to the first phase and later this can be tweaked, if required.

This was used to implicitly hydrate if you call ReactDOM.render.

We've had a warning to explicitly use ReactDOM.hydrate(...) instead of
ReactDOM.render(...). We can now remove this from the generated markup.
(And avoid adding it to Fizz.)

This is a little strange to do now since we're trying hard to make the
root API work the same.

But if we kept it, we'd need to keep it in the generated output which adds
unnecessary bytes. It also risks people relying on it, in the Fizz world
where as this is an opportunity to create that clean state.

We could possibly only keep it in the old server rendering APIs but then
that creates an implicit dependency between which server API and which
client API that you use. Currently you can really mix and match either way.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sebmarkbage/react/commits/689a783a3e59c9ac27e6127028fef15518913a9e"}]

[{"sha":"768c730086fb99a272b18f43aaa6af7e15bbef97","author":{"name":"Jakub Herkel","email":"03509b4f91cfe089fba3260bbac1c32f58d88909@uniq.sk"},"message":"[NETBEANS-5090] fix missing Serializable interface when a @ViewScoped CDI bean is created via JSF CDI Bean Wizard","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/768c730086fb99a272b18f43aaa6af7e15bbef97"},{"sha":"460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892","author":{"name":"Matthias Bläsing","email":"2733b4844ad39354bd21fd2bca55a8804e19a60d@doppel-helix.eu"},"message":"[NETBEANS-5380] Override generated ant projects for MX with NetBeans support

In profiles from repositry updater runs a huge CPU load originating 
from SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl was found. In parallel excessive runtimes
for project scanning were observed.

Comparing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl and SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation
the latter has an aggressive caching system, which results in much less
cpu usage. Just removing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl is not a solution, as
it is used to override the default project detection from
SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation.

Explanation from Jaroslav Tulach:

[...] Historically the Graal project provided mx netbeansinit support
which generates 8.2 Ant nbproject/project.xml projects based on content
of suite/mx.suite/suite.py. They were usually located in
suite/src/*/nbproject directories.

To fix this, the idea is, not only to use the current MX project
detection (it requires a folder `mx.proj` to be found in the project
folder `proj`), but also look two level ups from the current directory.
If that directory is recognised as a MX project, that project will
be returned as the project for the requested directory.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892"},{"sha":"2ccf4467602226a4becf95c41583d0ff82fd3423","author":{"name":"Svata Dedic","email":"023eb79affb3895450c68d8beb536005684ec349@oracle.com"},"message":"Trust priming build, as the user already saw the warning.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/2ccf4467602226a4becf95c41583d0ff82fd3423"},{"sha":"a04c16cb0ff0afe4ee565d360370fa5b4f169578","author":{"name":"Neil C Smith","email":"e98d4a33b51c12d4a3a2e22317e3af9557a6599a@apache.org"},"message":"Snapshot of APIs as of 12.3.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/a04c16cb0ff0afe4ee565d360370fa5b4f169578"},{"sha":"085718c35c16a53b667d4a4d0a75f46cb046d9c2","author":{"name":"Přemek Vyhnal","email":"ba4dd204299ff3080cf3373035325ee58babf0c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"fix travis link in readme","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Vitexus/netbeans/commits/085718c35c16a53b667d4a4d0a75f46cb046d9c2"},{"sha":"2691d4aed348ce2dc059131496d3c9fc251f8626","author":{"name":"Svatopluk Dedic","email":"023eb79affb3895450c68d8beb536005684ec349@oracle.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #2787 from sdedic/gradle/trustPrimingBuild

- to reduce binaries size of FFmpeg Windows wrapper
- MinGW linker doesn't support -ffunction-sections (used for FFmpeg Windows wrapper)
- move code to improve locality with its used dependencies
- move UMat::dot() to matmul.dispatch.cpp (Mat::dot() is already there)
- move UMat::inv() to lapack.cpp
- move UMat::mul() to arithm.cpp
- move UMat:eye() to matrix_operations.cpp (near setIdentity() implementation)
- move normalize(): convert_scale.cpp => norm.cpp
- move convertAndUnrollScalar(): arithm.cpp => copy.cpp
- move scalarToRawData(): array.cpp => copy.cpp
- move transpose(): matrix_operations.cpp => matrix_transform.cpp
- move flip(), rotate(): copy.cpp => matrix_transform.cpp (rotate90 uses flip and transpose)
- add 'OPENCV_CORE_EXCLUDE_C_API' CMake variable to exclude compilation of C-API functions from the core module
- matrix_wrap.cpp: add compile-time checks for CUDA/OpenGL calls
- the steps above allow to reduce FFmpeg wrapper size for ~1.5Mb (initial size of OpenCV part is about 3Mb)

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.
